
"In my work with other radical innovations ... experts are simply very conservative in their own field," Hoekstra tweeted. 

"A conservative mindset makes it possible to reject empirical data that suggests radical change." Specially true for the pace with which emerging economies are adapting

Moore's law (/mɔərz.ˈlɔː/) is the observation that the number of transistors in a dense integrated circuit doubles approximately every two years.

Swanson's law is an observation that the price of solar photovoltaic modules tends to drop 20 percent for every doubling of cumulative shipped volume.

